[?2004l[?2004h> # R2_18 = L1_18 xor P(R1) xor P(K1) xor 1    ... (2)
[?2004l[?2004h> # R3_18 = L2_18 xor P(R2) xor P(K2) xor 1    ... (3)
[?2004l[?2004h> # 
[?2004l[?2004h> # From (1): R1_18 is known if K0 known
[?2004l[?2004h> # From (2): R2_18 is known if R1 and K1 known
[?2004l[?2004h> # 
[?2004l[?2004h> # But I don't know K0, K1, K2. However, I can try to find K2 using
[?2004l[?2004h> # Matsui's last round attack on this reduced cipher.
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> # The 2-round approximation (rounds 0,1) would give:
[?2004l[?2004h> # R2_18 xor L0_18 xor P(R0') xor P(R1) = P(K0) xor P(K1)  ... combining (1) and (2)
[?2004l[?2004h> # Wait, let me trace correctly.
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> # From (1): R1_18 = L0_18 xor P(R0') xor P(K0) xor 1
[?2004l[?2004h> # From (2): R2_18 = L1_18 xor P(R1) xor P(K1) xor 1
[?2004l[?2004h> # 
[?2004l[?2004h> # Substituting L1 = R0' and R1 from (1):
[?2004l[?2004h> # R2_18 = R0_18 xor P(R1) xor P(K1) xor 1  ... (where R0_18 is bit 18 of R0, but L1_18 = (R0')_18 = R0_18 xor L0_18)
[?2004l[?2004h> # Wait, L1 = R0' = R0 xor L0, so L1_18 = R0_18 xor L0_18
[?2004l[?2004h> # 
[?2004l[?2004h> # So:
