[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> # This is getting messy. Let me just implement the same linear attack for K2.
[?2004l[?2004h> # For the 3-round cipher (ending at round 2), I want a 2-round approximation
[?2004l[?2004h> # involving K0, K1 and then guess K2.
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> # Actually, I can use the SAME approach as for K3! 
[?2004l[?2004h> # The 2-round linear approximation:
[?2004l[?2004h> # R2_18 xor L0_18 xor P(R0') xor P(L2) = P(K0) xor P(K2?) 
[?2004l[?2004h> # Wait no, the round-2 equation involves K2 directly.
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> # Let me use the following:
[?2004l[?2004h> # From rounds 0,1,2:
[?2004l[?2004h> # R3_18 = L2_18 xor P(R2) xor P(K2) xor 1 = R1_18 xor P(R2) xor P(K2) xor 1
[?2004l[?2004h> # R2_18 = L1_18 xor P(R1) xor P(K1) xor 1 = R0_18 xor L0_18 xor P(R1) xor P(K1) xor 1
[?2004l[?2004h> # R1_18 = L0_18 xor P(R0') xor P(K0) xor 1
[?2004l[?2004h> # 
[?2004l[?2004h> # I want an equation involving (L0,R0) and (L3,R3) and only ONE unknown key (K2).
[?2004l[?2004h> # 
[?2004l[?2004h> # Looking at equation (3): R3_18 = L2_18 xor P(R2) xor P(K2) xor 1
[?2004l[?2004h> # I know R3_18 from (L3,R3) (after partial decrypt with K3).
[?2004l[?2004h> # I know L2_18 = R1_18 (since L2 = R1). But R1_18 is unknown...
[?2004l[?2004h> # 
[?2004l[?2004h> # However, I can guess K2 and check consistency across pairs!
[?2004l[?2004h> # The equation for each pair:
[?2004l[?2004h> # R3_18 xor L2_18 xor P(R2) xor 1 = P(K2) (a constant bit)
[?2004l[?2004h> # Where L2 = R1, and R2 = L3.
