[?2004l[?2004h> # Let me just brute-force K2 (2^20) and K1 (2^20) and K0 (2^20) using the known K3
[?2004l[?2004h> # and check against the 32 pairs. But 2^40 is still too large.
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> # Wait, I can use the fact that after peeling off round 3, we have a 3-round cipher.
[?2004l[?2004h> # For this 3-round cipher, I can use the SAME linear attack to find K2!
[?2004l[?2004h> # The equation would be:
[?2004l[?2004h> # R2_18 xor L1_18 xor P(R1) xor P(L2) = P(K0) xor P(K1) 
